    <p>Given <m>\vrt</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, there are infinite vectors orthogonal to the tangent vector at a given point. Again, we might wonder <q>Is one of these infinite choices preferable over the others? Is one of these the `right' choice?</q></p>

    <p>The answer in both <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is <q>Yes, there is one vector that is not only preferable, it is the `right' one to choose.</q> Recall <xref ref="thm_vects_of_constant_length">Theorem</xref>, which states that if <m>\vrt</m> has constant length, then <m>\vrt</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vrp(t)</m> for all <m>t</m>. We know <m>\vec T(t)</m>, the unit tangent vector, has constant length. Therefore <m>\vec T(t)</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vec T\,'(t)</m>.<index><main>vector-valued function</main><sub>of constant length</sub></index></p>

    <p>We'll see that <m>\vec T\,'(t)</m> is more than just a convenient choice of vector that is orthogonal to <m>\vrp(t)</m>; rather, it is the <q>right</q> choice. Since all we care about is the direction, we define this newly found vector to be a unit vector.</p>

    <aside>
      <p><m>\vec T(t)</m> is a unit vector, by definition. This <em>does not</em> imply that <m>\vec T\,'(t)</m> is also a unit vector.</p>
    </aside>

    <definition xml:id="def_unit_normal">
      <title>Unit Normal Vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vrt</m> be a vector-valued function where the unit tangent vector, <m>\vec T(t)</m>, is smooth on an open interval <m>I</m>. The <term>unit normal vector</term> <m>\vec N(t)</m> is
          <index><main>unit normal vector</main><sub>definition</sub></index><index><main>unit vector</main><sub>unit normal vector</sub></index>
          <me>
            \vec N(t) = \frac1{\norm{\vec T\,'(t)}}\vec T\,'(t).
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex_tannorm3">
      <title>Computing the unit normal vector</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vrt = \la 3\cos(t) , 3\sin(t) , 4t\ra</m> as in <xref ref="ex_tannorm1">Example</xref>. Sketch both <m>\vec T(\pi/2)</m> and <m>\vec N(\pi/2)</m> with initial points at <m>\vec r(\pi/2)</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>In <xref ref="ex_tannorm1">Example</xref>, we found <m>\vec T(t) = \la  (-3/5)\sin(t) ,(3/5)\cos(t) ,4/5\ra</m>. Therefore
          <me>
            \vec T\,'(t) = \la -\frac35\cos(t) ,-\frac35\sin(t) ,0\ra \text{ and }   \norm{\vec T\,'(t)} = \frac35.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>Thus
          <me>
            \vec N(t) = \frac{\vec T\,'(t)}{3/5} = \la -\cos(t) ,-\sin(t) ,0\ra.
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>We compute <m>\vec T(\pi/2) = \la -3/5,0,4/5\ra</m> and <m>\vec N(\pi/2) = \la 0,-1,0\ra</m>. These are sketched in <xref ref="fig_tannorm3">Figure</xref>.</p>

