            <p><m>a_{\text{T} } = \frac{4t}{\sqrt{1+4t^2}}</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = \sqrt{4-\frac{16t^2}{1+4t^2}}</m></p>

            <p>At <m>t=0</m>, <m>a_{\text{T} } = 0</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = 2</m>;</p>

            <p>At <m>t=1</m>, <m>a_{\text{T} } = 4/\sqrt{5}</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = 2/\sqrt{5}</m>.</p>

            <p>At <m>t=0</m>, all acceleration comes in the form of changing the direction of velocity and not the speed; at <m>t=1</m>, more acceleration comes in changing the speed than in changing direction.</p>
