          <solution>
            <p><m>a_{\text{T} } = 0</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = a</m></p>

            <p>At <m>t=0</m>, <m>a_{\text{T} } = 0</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = a</m>;</p>

            <p>At <m>t=\pi/2</m>, <m>a_{\text{T} } = 0</m> and <m>a_{\text{N} } = a</m>.</p>

            <p>The object moves at constant speed, meaning that <m>a_{\text{T} }</m> is always 0. The object <q>rises</q> along the <m>z</m>-axis at a constant rate, so all acceleration comes in the form of changing direction circling the <m>z</m>-axis. The greater the radius of this circle the greater the acceleration, hence <m>a_{\text{N} }=a</m>.</p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
